Good grief.

02:01.360 --> 02:03.317
Are you just coming home?

02:03.560 --> 02:05.791
Shh. Are they still sleeping?

02:06.000 --> 02:07.000
My goodness.

02:07.160 --> 02:09.880
You stay out all night,
you sleep all day.

02:10.080 --> 02:12.879
The only time I get a chance
to clean your room is midnight.

02:13.440 --> 02:15.796
Come on, Benson.
I got enough problems.

02:16.000 --> 02:17.321
It's unhealthy,
that's what it is.

02:17.440 --> 02:20.592
You never see the sun,
you don't eat regular meals.

02:20.800 --> 02:23.395
You hardly ever even stand up.

02:26.360 --> 02:29.034
You better get a job, girl.

02:30.160 --> 02:31.160
[GASPS]

02:31.320 --> 02:32.993
Oh!
Morning, Ma.

02:33.200 --> 02:34.953
My goodness,
you're up bright and early.

02:35.160 --> 02:36.753
Oh, well...

02:36.960 --> 02:38.792
Well, I was just leaving.
I'm, uh...

02:39.000 --> 02:40.559
I'm going out to look for a job.

02:40.800 --> 02:42.917
As a night watchman.

02:43.720 --> 02:45.518
Well, I'll see you later, Ma.

02:45.720 --> 02:49.555
Yes, good luck with the job.
Oh, thanks.

02:51.600 --> 02:52.600
Benson.
Huh?

02:52.800 --> 02:54.553
Why isn't the table set
for breakfast?

02:54.760 --> 02:56.638
Because I didn't set it.

02:56.840 --> 02:58.718
Oh, well, I suppose
that's a good reason.

02:58.960 --> 03:01.480
And I ain't gonna set it.
Oh, Benson, you have to set the table.

03:01.600 --> 03:02.636
I mean, we have to eat.

03:02.840 --> 03:04.752
People in this house
don't eat breakfast.

03:04.960 --> 03:07.270
They run in, bend over,
sip and leave.

03:07.480 --> 03:10.871
So that's it for table setting.
Table setting is out.

03:11.120 --> 03:12.315
Jessica?
JESSICA: Yes, dear.

03:12.520 --> 03:14.477
Where's breakfast?
The dining room is empty.

03:14.680 --> 03:15.680
I know, dear.

03:15.840 --> 03:19.436
We're having a kind of a buffet
in the kitchen this morning.

03:19.640 --> 03:22.678
Chester, how would you like for me
to make you some waffles?

03:22.920 --> 03:26.197
Just toast and coffee.
Ah.

03:28.400 --> 03:30.517
Benson?
Hm?

03:30.720 --> 03:33.918
Why is it everyone else's toast
is always a nice, normal colour,

03:34.120 --> 03:35.918
and mine is always black?

03:41.560 --> 03:44.837
Black ain't a nice,
normal colour?

03:45.360 --> 03:47.511
I'm talking about toast, Benson.

03:49.320 --> 03:52.392
Now, why is mine black?

03:53.240 --> 03:55.357
Because it's burnt.

03:57.480 --> 03:58.834
Why don't we fire him?

03:59.040 --> 04:02.078
Oh, don't be silly, darling.
We can't fire Benson.

04:02.320 --> 04:03.959
What do you mean, we can't?

04:04.200 --> 04:06.317
Nobody but Benson
would put up with us.

04:06.560 --> 04:11.237
What are you talking about,
Jessica? We're a perfectly
nice, normal family.

04:12.000 --> 04:14.071
Good morning, Daddy.

04:14.640 --> 04:16.632
MAJOR:
Where have I landed?

04:16.880 --> 04:19.349
In the kitchen, you idiot.

04:20.360 --> 04:21.430
Oh, colonel!

04:21.640 --> 04:25.111
I was afraid the wind had
blown me behind enemy lines.

04:25.320 --> 04:26.913
Here, Daddy.
Hi, Gramps.

04:27.120 --> 04:28.600
There's nobody
in the dining room.

04:28.800 --> 04:31.395
I know, dear.
We're all in here.

04:31.600 --> 04:34.434
Could Mommy fix you a nice
bowl of cereal for breakfast?

04:34.640 --> 04:36.199
No, thanks, Ma.

04:36.400 --> 04:39.120
You got home
very late last night.

04:39.360 --> 04:40.999
Yeah, I know. I had a date.

04:41.240 --> 04:43.436
Uh, you know, Billy,
I think maybe it's time

04:43.640 --> 04:46.439
that you and I had
a little man-to-man talk.

04:46.680 --> 04:49.275
Ah, that's all right, Dad.
Benson took care of that already.

04:53.040 --> 04:55.077
Benson took care of what?

04:55.320 --> 04:58.040
Sex. See, we also
learned it in school.

04:58.240 --> 05:01.870
Of course, in school,
they teach us about chickens
and fruit flies mating, you know.

05:02.640 --> 05:07.510
Chester, what would
a chicken see in a fruit fly?

05:14.960 --> 05:17.680
I don't know, Jessica.

05:19.080 --> 05:21.160
I don't know why they
have to teach us about animals.

05:21.320 --> 05:23.039
Benson told it better.

05:23.280 --> 05:26.910
Well, I'm sure that Benson,
in his primitive way,

05:27.120 --> 05:29.077
explained things to you.

05:29.280 --> 05:33.638
But I think it's a good idea if you
had the right view of things.

05:33.840 --> 05:36.150
The white view?

05:37.120 --> 05:41.319
Chester, do whites
and blacks do it differently?

05:43.200 --> 05:46.272
I said, "the right view,"
Jessica.

05:47.280 --> 05:48.999
Well, I know how it works, Dad.

05:49.200 --> 05:53.194
Unfortunately, it hasn't
changed my life any.

06:14.000 --> 06:16.276
He just drank raw eggs.

06:16.480 --> 06:18.836
You just ate burnt toast.

06:19.720 --> 06:21.154
Morning, everyone. Daddy.

06:21.360 --> 06:23.192
Morning, princess.
Good morning, darling.

06:23.400 --> 06:26.757
Eunice, how would you like
some pancakes for breakfast?

06:27.000 --> 06:29.560
Oh, no, thank you, Mother.
I'm on 300 calories a day.

06:29.800 --> 06:32.679
Three hundred calories?
But, darling, what can you eat?

06:32.920 --> 06:37.119
Nothing. If I brush my teeth twice
a day, that puts me a little over.

06:37.360 --> 06:38.635
[LAUGHS]

06:41.520 --> 06:43.989
How would you like a ride
to the station, puss?

06:44.200 --> 06:47.352
Oh, no, thanks, Daddy.
I'm flying to Washington
to cover a press conference.

06:47.560 --> 06:50.120
Ah. Careful of those
congressmen.

06:50.360 --> 06:51.999
Too late.

06:54.600 --> 07:01.279
Jessica, would you tell Benson
to starch my shirts, not my shorts?

07:01.480 --> 07:05.599
I feel like I'm walking around
with saltines in my pants.

07:06.320 --> 07:08.516
I better get going, Mother.
I'll be home tonight.

07:08.720 --> 07:10.439
All right, darling.
Have a safe trip.

07:10.640 --> 07:12.632
Bye-bye, Major.

07:13.280 --> 07:15.749
One thing I like about
you Italian women.

07:15.960 --> 07:18.156
You're very grateful.

07:18.600 --> 07:19.716
Maybe this evening,

07:19.920 --> 07:23.914
I'll bring you some nylon
stockings and Hershey bars.

07:24.680 --> 07:27.434
Mother, this war thing
is getting worse and worse.

07:27.640 --> 07:30.030
He doesn't even know
where he is anymore.

07:30.240 --> 07:31.390
His mind...

07:31.600 --> 07:36.800
Mind! Young lady,
I'll have you know my mind
is sharp as candy, thank God.

07:37.000 --> 07:38.593
Come in.

07:42.840 --> 07:45.150
[♪♪♪]

07:49.640 --> 07:52.792
Listen, babe, I hate
to rush you, but I got
another lesson real soon.

07:53.000 --> 07:56.755
The real reason I came here
today was to break up with you.

07:57.040 --> 07:58.040
[CHUCKLES]

07:58.200 --> 07:59.429
Break up with me?
Yeah.

07:59.680 --> 08:01.433
I mean, ironic, isn't it?
Yeah.

08:01.640 --> 08:04.872
See, I mean,
I let this happen once before,

08:05.080 --> 08:08.391
but I came here today to tell you
I could never let it happen again.

08:08.600 --> 08:11.195
And then I mean, I no sooner
than get here than I let happen

08:11.400 --> 08:13.835
exactly what I said
I would never let happen again.

08:14.080 --> 08:15.753
Yeah, what happens
happens, you know.

08:15.960 --> 08:18.270
Yes, but I mean,
why did it happen?

08:18.800 --> 08:21.315
Do you think maybe
I'm in love with you?

08:22.520 --> 08:24.159
You're not, no.
Well, maybe.

08:24.360 --> 08:28.354
I mean, my stomach goes
flip-flop and I'm all shivery.

08:28.800 --> 08:31.838
Oh, that's the flu, the intestinal flu.
I had it myself, last week.

08:32.039 --> 08:34.191
I think you should go
right home and get to bed.

08:34.440 --> 08:37.274
Oh, I hope my mother
isn't looking down
from heaven at this.

08:37.480 --> 08:39.789
I mean, this would kill her.

08:40.000 --> 08:42.231
This is not love.
This is the flu.

08:42.440 --> 08:45.353
Then, of course, if my mother
is looking down from heaven,

08:45.560 --> 08:50.032
being very nearsighted,
maybe she wouldn't know
it was me anyway.

08:50.240 --> 08:54.120
Then again, maybe in heaven,
people aren't nearsighted.

08:54.320 --> 08:57.199
I mean, if there is
a life after death,

08:57.400 --> 08:59.517
I wonder if you need
glasses for it.

09:00.320 --> 09:01.356
Mother!

09:02.400 --> 09:03.516
Corinne!

09:04.800 --> 09:06.712
Corinne, hello, I...

09:06.920 --> 09:09.310
I was just at the end
of my tennis lesson.

09:09.520 --> 09:11.637
See, I, uh...
I take my lessons up here,

09:11.840 --> 09:14.958
because the lines on the court
make me so nervous.

09:15.160 --> 09:16.913
That's right, the lines.

09:17.160 --> 09:20.995
Peter thought of this.
This sort of takes the
pressure off. You know?

09:21.200 --> 09:23.920
Keep your knees
bent now and follow
through with the racket.

09:24.120 --> 09:25.634
Yeah.
Over the shoulder.

09:25.880 --> 09:27.553
PETER: I think you're getting it.
JESSICA: I got it.

09:27.760 --> 09:29.479
There, you got it. Good!
I got it.

09:30.160 --> 09:31.674
I got it.
I think you've got it.

09:31.880 --> 09:33.633
Yeah, and thank you.

09:33.840 --> 09:35.832
I got it. Bye.
PETER: See you next week. Bye.

09:38.520 --> 09:39.954
She's really improving.

09:41.400 --> 09:42.436
Really...

09:43.600 --> 09:45.159
improving.

09:45.400 --> 09:47.153
[♪♪♪]

09:47.640 --> 09:50.235
And you don't have to be
a baseball player to use Ball 4.

09:50.440 --> 09:54.195
After the game, I always use it
for the game that's coming up.

09:54.440 --> 09:56.352
And cut. Good.
I think we got it.

09:56.560 --> 09:59.029
Thank you.
That's a wrap, everybody.

09:59.240 --> 10:01.357
All right. Thank you.

10:01.880 --> 10:04.156
Thank you very much.
Well, how'd it look?

10:04.400 --> 10:05.400
Terrific.
Good.

10:05.640 --> 10:07.791
Listen, if you need tickets to a game
sometime, just let me know.

10:08.000 --> 10:10.480
I'll take you up on that.
Hey, how about this Sunday,
49er game?

10:10.600 --> 10:11.829
Done.
Out of sight. Great.

10:12.040 --> 10:14.396
That's gonna be a great game.
They got a great defence,
toughest in the league.

10:14.640 --> 10:16.001
All right, Dennis,
what's going on?

10:16.200 --> 10:18.920
You broke two dates
with me in the last week.

10:21.040 --> 10:24.078
I told you, I had a terrible week.
I mean, I had a rough game Sunday.

10:24.320 --> 10:26.835
It's not just that, Dennis.
It's a lot of little things.

10:27.040 --> 10:28.713
I mean, you're different.
Well, how?

10:28.920 --> 10:31.196
How? Like Friday night
when we went out for dinner.

10:31.440 --> 10:33.272
You asked for a table
instead of a booth.

10:33.480 --> 10:35.631
You spent the whole meal
talking to those people next to us.

10:35.840 --> 10:38.560
And then you tell me,
"I have a headache."

10:39.480 --> 10:42.678
I did. I got kicked
in the head in practise.

10:42.920 --> 10:44.115
Is there another guy?

10:44.360 --> 10:45.510
Oh, come on, Jodie.

10:45.760 --> 10:47.479
It's Ralph, isn't it?
It's not Ralph.

10:47.680 --> 10:49.399
Fine, hey, you wanna be
with Ralph, be with Ralph.

10:49.600 --> 10:51.512
I mean, the man has
the IQ of an avocado

10:51.720 --> 10:54.235
and the worst nose job
that I've ever seen.

10:54.440 --> 10:56.557
It's not Ralph.
It's David, then, hm?

10:56.760 --> 10:58.638
It's not David.
Because he lied, Dennis.

10:58.840 --> 11:01.912
He was never Barbra
Streisand's hairdresser.

11:02.160 --> 11:03.160
It's not David.

11:03.360 --> 11:04.874
It's Bob. It's Bob.

11:05.080 --> 11:07.200
Jodie, it's not another guy.
Then what the heck is it?

11:07.760 --> 11:09.160
Well, it's...

11:09.360 --> 11:10.396
It's a woman.

11:10.640 --> 11:13.200
Oh, be serious.
I am.

11:13.720 --> 11:14.756
Come on, Dennis.

11:14.960 --> 11:17.111
When you're at the line of
scrimmage, read the blitz.

11:17.320 --> 11:20.313
Dump it off over the middle,
throw a zing out for a quick six.

11:20.520 --> 11:22.432
A woman?

11:22.640 --> 11:23.960
You and a woman?

11:24.760 --> 11:26.638
Some people wouldn't find
that so strange.

11:26.840 --> 11:27.990
Oh, I know that, Dennis.

11:28.200 --> 11:30.795
But, you know, seeing as
you're a homosexual, I would...

11:31.000 --> 11:32.753
[GIGGLING]

11:34.200 --> 11:36.510
A woman. Does she know?

11:37.560 --> 11:38.835
I haven't told her yet.

11:39.080 --> 11:42.710
Well, Dennis, when you
touch her and throw up, I think
she's gonna be suspicious.

11:45.120 --> 11:46.713
I'll tell her. I'll tell her.

11:47.720 --> 11:49.632
A woman!

11:52.120 --> 11:53.952
What's so funny?
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

11:54.160 --> 11:56.800
I'm just having a little trouble
picturing it, that's all.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.231
I mean, what do you do with her?

11:59.440 --> 12:02.160
Listen, Jodie, it just so happens
I might be a latent heterosexual.

12:02.360 --> 12:03.360
Oh, really?
Yeah.

12:03.560 --> 12:05.995
Oh, and what makes
you think you have these
heterosexual tendencies?

12:06.200 --> 12:08.669
Just because you're not
crazy about Bette Midler?

12:11.280 --> 12:13.511
Look, it has nothing
to do with us.

12:13.720 --> 12:15.074
I mean, it's just too risky.

12:15.280 --> 12:17.600
You know, I've only got
a couple of years of pro ball left.

12:17.680 --> 12:20.036
And after that, I've gotta
rely on making money
from my endorsements.

12:20.240 --> 12:22.516
I mean, if people found out I was a...
Homosexual!

12:22.720 --> 12:24.791
Shh! Shh!

12:25.000 --> 12:28.391
All right. All right.
I'm sorry. Sorry.

12:28.600 --> 12:31.160
But I kind of
figured this was coming,
so I worked out a solution.

12:31.320 --> 12:33.960
What?
Well, it's a pretty big step.

12:34.160 --> 12:35.480
Sex-change operation.

12:36.080 --> 12:38.276
A sex-change operation?

12:38.480 --> 12:39.480
[WHISTLES]

12:40.720 --> 12:42.518
Which one of us?

12:43.840 --> 12:46.833
Since you're the quarterback,
I guess it would be me.

12:47.040 --> 12:48.394
You mean, you'd become a woman?

12:48.640 --> 12:51.951
Mm-hm. The doctor said I would
look just like Jacqueline Bisset.

12:52.160 --> 12:55.358
I don't know. This would
solve the problem, but...

12:55.560 --> 12:56.630
But what?

12:56.840 --> 12:59.878
The responsibility.
I don't want the responsibility.

13:00.080 --> 13:02.549
What if it didn't work out
between us, if I left you?

13:02.760 --> 13:05.001
I mean, you'd be stuck being
a woman, and I'd feel awful.

13:05.040 --> 13:08.112
Oh, no, you wouldn't.
You'd be dead.

13:08.360 --> 13:10.317
[♪♪♪]

13:15.160 --> 13:17.072
[♪♪♪]

13:17.280 --> 13:20.557
Chester. Chester,
what's the matter with you?
You're a nervous wreck.

13:20.800 --> 13:23.952
Of course I'm nervous,
Claire. I told you I didn't
want to come here.

13:24.160 --> 13:27.119
I cancelled a very
important business lunch
to come here today.

13:27.320 --> 13:29.232
Do you know how
embarrassing it would be

13:29.440 --> 13:31.636
if the man I was to have
had lunch with walked in?

13:31.880 --> 13:33.758
And who were you supposed
to have lunch with?

13:34.000 --> 13:36.276
Matt Sloan.
Really?

13:36.480 --> 13:40.679
How brave of him to join
you for lunch the day
after open-heart surgery.

13:40.880 --> 13:44.999
I mean, to come here,
wired up to all those machines.

13:46.280 --> 13:48.351
What are you talking about,
Claire?

13:48.560 --> 13:50.756
Matt Sloan.
Matt Sloan?

13:50.960 --> 13:53.031
I said Marty Simms.

13:53.240 --> 13:54.833
How can I have lunch
with Matt Sloan?

13:55.040 --> 13:57.919
He's in intensive care,
for God's sake.

13:58.120 --> 14:02.239
Do you think Mount Sinai lets you out
of intensive care for a lunch hour?

14:02.440 --> 14:04.397
[LAUGHING]

14:06.840 --> 14:08.479
Marty Simms?
Right.

14:08.680 --> 14:10.399
Well, it must have been
very important.

14:10.600 --> 14:13.832
I mean, since Marty Simms
is vacationing in the south
of France,

14:14.040 --> 14:16.191
this must have been
some important lunch.

14:16.440 --> 14:18.796
That's right. That's precisely
how important it was.

14:19.000 --> 14:23.552
Marty Simms was going to hop on
the Concorde to get here in time.

14:23.760 --> 14:26.559
Crazy Marty.

14:27.440 --> 14:30.592
Chester, I've been your secretary
for 12 years. You can't lie to me.

14:30.800 --> 14:32.871
You were going
to have lunch with Pigeon.

14:33.120 --> 14:34.120
Pigeon?

14:34.320 --> 14:37.836
Oh, Claire, how many times
do I have to tell you?

14:38.040 --> 14:39.633
Pigeon and I are through.

14:39.880 --> 14:42.111
Save it, Chester.
I swear it, Claire. I swear it.

14:42.360 --> 14:45.034
Chester, it's been 12 years
I've been doing things for you.

14:45.240 --> 14:48.199
From now on, you're going
to be doing things for me.

14:48.400 --> 14:51.359
The lovely condominium
that you bought me was
just the beginning.

14:51.600 --> 14:53.910
I need...
Claire, I really can't afford...

14:54.120 --> 14:56.112
Chester, what you
really can't afford

14:56.320 --> 14:59.074
is an investigation by the
Securities Exchange Commission.

14:59.280 --> 15:02.079
I mean, that's what you
really can't afford, Chester.

15:02.320 --> 15:05.597
Claire, Claire, Claire.

15:06.120 --> 15:08.794
You little hothead, you.

15:09.000 --> 15:12.676
All of this is unnecessary,
you know that.

15:12.920 --> 15:16.197
It's you, my sweet.
It's always been you.

15:16.400 --> 15:18.790
It always will be you.

15:19.000 --> 15:21.595
Chester, you
double-crossing,

15:21.840 --> 15:24.116
dirty, lying cheat.
Ah, ah! Miss Teitelbaum.

15:24.360 --> 15:27.194
I was trying to reach you.
Your stock has...

15:27.400 --> 15:29.517
Minor problem in her account.

15:29.720 --> 15:32.280
She's so short that her stock...

15:32.480 --> 15:34.949
I don't know what
you're thinking, but...

15:35.920 --> 15:38.355
Now I know.

15:41.120 --> 15:44.033
Well, so much for Pigeon.

15:44.560 --> 15:47.473
Now, Chester, there is one
last thing I want you to do for me.

15:48.080 --> 15:50.675
What's that?

15:50.920 --> 15:51.956
Divorce Jessica.

15:52.440 --> 15:54.397
What are you talking about,
Claire? I can't...

15:54.640 --> 15:58.270
You've been saying you're
going to do it for 12 years.
Now, think about it, Chester.

15:58.480 --> 16:01.359
It's either me and a two-week
honeymoon in the Bahamas,

16:01.560 --> 16:04.997
or Jessica and 10 to 20 in Attica.

16:06.280 --> 16:07.634
So, Chester, what do you say?

16:10.160 --> 16:12.436
What were the choices again?

16:13.000 --> 16:14.957
[♪♪♪]

16:16.120 --> 16:17.952
I just love having tea.

16:18.160 --> 16:21.312
I always feel like
such a lady having tea.

16:21.520 --> 16:24.080
Of course, the way things
have been going lately,

16:24.280 --> 16:28.194
it would take a great deal
more than tea to make me
feel like a lady.

16:28.440 --> 16:31.956
In fact, I wonder if I'll
ever feel like a lady again.

16:32.200 --> 16:34.280
Jessie, don't you think
you ought to stop seeing him?

16:34.440 --> 16:36.830
Somehow, I don't think
you're cut out for this.

16:37.080 --> 16:38.480
Well, of course, you know,

16:38.680 --> 16:42.959
Scarlett O' Hara
always felt like a lady,
no matter what she did.

16:43.160 --> 16:44.310
Jessie, what do you think?

16:44.520 --> 16:46.671
Well, I think it was all the
hoop skirts and parasols.

16:46.880 --> 16:50.191
I mean, how could you not
feel like a lady with all that?

16:50.440 --> 16:52.955
Jessie.
Oh, Mary, I feel awful.

16:53.160 --> 16:56.153
I am absolutely no good
at carrying on.

16:56.360 --> 16:58.113
I mean, some people are
very good at it.

16:58.320 --> 17:00.960
You know, they just go out
and have a good time. But not me.

17:01.160 --> 17:03.117
I mean, when I go out
to have a good time,

17:03.320 --> 17:05.152
I have a terrible time
having it.

17:06.359 --> 17:09.910
Also, Corinne almost caught me
today in Peter's apartment.

17:10.160 --> 17:11.833
No!
Mm.

17:12.040 --> 17:15.636
But I very cleverly pretended
I was learning to serve.

17:15.880 --> 17:19.794
Jessie, don't see him anymore.

17:20.000 --> 17:22.992
For all you know, he could be
carrying on with a lot of women.

17:23.240 --> 17:25.391
He could be carrying on
with Corinne.

17:25.640 --> 17:29.350
Oh, Mary, don't be silly.
Corinne is a baby.

17:29.600 --> 17:31.751
Jessie, Corinne is not a baby.

17:31.960 --> 17:35.431
I heard Eunice say that Corinne
doesn't even come home at night.

17:35.680 --> 17:38.070
That's because she refuses
to wear a watch.

17:38.320 --> 17:40.551
She has...

17:41.240 --> 17:45.996
Mary, I'm telling you, Corinne has
absolutely no sense of time.

17:46.200 --> 17:50.353
You know, sometimes she
actually says "Good morning"
when it's afternoon.

17:50.560 --> 17:53.394
That's the way she is.
Absolutely no sense of time.

17:53.600 --> 17:56.354
But a wonderful sense
of direction.

17:57.800 --> 18:00.190
Jessie, that's not true.

18:00.400 --> 18:01.516
Sugar, Mary?

18:01.720 --> 18:04.110
Jessie, you know about Corinne.
Cream?

18:04.320 --> 18:07.199
Jessie, Corinne sleeps out.

18:07.400 --> 18:10.199
Lemon?
Jessica!

18:11.280 --> 18:14.796
Jessie, you can't play
ostrich all the time.

18:15.000 --> 18:18.516
Sometimes you have to
open your eyes and see
what's going on in the world.

18:18.760 --> 18:20.558
I know, Mary. I know.

18:20.760 --> 18:25.152
And I would, if there were lovely,
beautiful things to look at.

18:25.360 --> 18:26.714
But there aren't, Mary.

18:26.960 --> 18:30.749
Jessie, life can't
always be beautiful.

18:31.000 --> 18:34.152
It can. Mary, it can,
if you think it can.

18:34.360 --> 18:36.317
Besides, even if Corinne
did wear a watch,

18:36.520 --> 18:38.477
she probably wouldn't
come home at night.

18:38.680 --> 18:40.353
You know, it's in her blood.

18:43.080 --> 18:44.594
What are you talking about?

18:44.840 --> 18:47.116
Mary, you know she's adopted.

18:47.320 --> 18:48.834
Of course,
she doesn't know that.

18:49.040 --> 18:51.077
But you remember
what her mother was like.

18:51.280 --> 18:56.036
And frankly, I think she's inherited
the trait of staying out all night.

18:56.560 --> 18:59.758
Somehow, I don't think
that's inherited, Jess.

19:00.000 --> 19:04.358
I don't know why not.
Eye colour and money is.

19:06.160 --> 19:08.311
Jessie, what are you gonna do?

19:08.520 --> 19:10.398
Go to the bathroom.
It's the tea.

19:10.600 --> 19:12.159
I don't know how
the English do it.

19:12.360 --> 19:14.920
They must be up and down
every five minutes.

19:15.120 --> 19:17.715
No. About Peter.

19:17.960 --> 19:20.191
Oh, I'm never going
to see him again.

19:20.760 --> 19:22.956
Really?
Really, never again.

19:23.200 --> 19:25.999
Oh, good.
Jess, that's wise.

19:26.200 --> 19:29.716
And I'm going to tell him, too,
just as soon as I see him.

19:30.440 --> 19:31.999
Jessie, wait.

19:32.200 --> 19:33.953
[♪♪♪]

19:34.160 --> 19:36.959
And this is my room.
Typical.

19:37.400 --> 19:38.595
Those are hamsters.

19:38.840 --> 19:41.480
No, I thought
they were water buffalo.

19:42.920 --> 19:45.435
So, Molly, I haven't got
all the time in the world.

19:45.640 --> 19:46.960
Are we going steady or what?

19:47.160 --> 19:50.631
Not that it matters one way
or another. If it's not you,
it's somebody else.

19:50.880 --> 19:52.758
And why do we have to go steady?

19:53.000 --> 19:55.071
Because everybody is.
It's no big deal.

19:56.240 --> 19:57.469
Okay, fine. Forget it.

19:57.720 --> 20:00.599
Well, I have to think about it.
What's there to think about?

20:00.840 --> 20:03.878
Well, I don't know
if I want to get tied down.

20:04.120 --> 20:05.600
Fine, forget it.

20:05.840 --> 20:10.517
Well, this isn't a yes, but if we
were to happen to go steady,
what exactly do we do?

20:10.760 --> 20:13.434
I told you. You wear something
of mine and that's it.

20:13.680 --> 20:16.275
What, shoes?
No, a ring or a bracelet.

20:16.480 --> 20:18.233
Do you have one?
No.

20:18.480 --> 20:21.439
Listen, I think next time
you ask a girl to go steady,

20:21.640 --> 20:23.757
you should prepare
a little for it.

20:23.960 --> 20:25.314
Wait, I got it.

20:25.520 --> 20:30.037
You can wear this on a chain.

20:30.280 --> 20:32.556
What is it?
That's a genuine shark's tooth.

20:32.800 --> 20:35.110
Gross! Haven't you
got something gold?

20:35.360 --> 20:36.999
What's wrong with the tooth?

20:38.520 --> 20:42.400
I mean, Judy has Eric's ring
and Tracy has Sam's football charm.

20:42.600 --> 20:44.717
Stephanie has a silver
thingamajig from Ronnie.

20:44.920 --> 20:46.559
Everybody's wearing
silver and gold.

20:46.760 --> 20:49.559
And I'm not wearing
a tooth from a fish.

20:49.800 --> 20:53.794
Okay, fine. I'll get you something.
And if I do, are you gonna wear it?

20:54.000 --> 20:56.120
Well, I don't know.
What if I want to date other guys?

20:56.240 --> 20:58.994
What are you talking about?
You don't even date.

20:59.520 --> 21:01.591
And it doesn't mean
you can kiss me.

21:01.840 --> 21:04.878
Who wants to kiss you?
I don't want to kiss you.
Kissing is gross.

21:05.080 --> 21:07.549
So, what's it gonna be?
I haven't got all day.

21:09.120 --> 21:10.793
Hey, what's this?

21:11.000 --> 21:12.992
I won it for swimming.
I'll take it.

21:13.200 --> 21:14.953
My medal!
Yeah.

21:15.200 --> 21:16.919
That's the medal
I won for swimming!

21:17.160 --> 21:18.674
Do you want to go steady or not?

21:18.920 --> 21:20.639
All right. All right.
You can keep it.

21:20.840 --> 21:22.672
So does this mean
we're going steady now?

21:22.920 --> 21:23.956
Yeah. See you.

21:26.240 --> 21:27.833
My medal!

21:28.040 --> 21:29.997
[♪♪♪]

21:38.840 --> 21:41.036
Oh, hi, Danny boy,
Am I glad you're here.

21:41.240 --> 21:44.870
I started to make a sandwich,
I got a little carried away.
You can share it with me.

21:45.080 --> 21:48.391
Oh, if your mother saw
what I was making right
before dinner, she'd kill me.

21:48.600 --> 21:50.671
She always thinks
I'm gonna ruin my appetite.

21:50.880 --> 21:52.599
[STAMMERING]

21:52.800 --> 21:55.520
Danny, Danny, you did it.
You quit the Mob.

21:55.720 --> 21:57.996
And you're giving me your gun.

21:58.480 --> 22:01.791
Oh, I'm so proud of you,
Danny. So proud.

22:02.680 --> 22:05.559
I can't believe this.
I can't believe what's
going on here.

22:05.760 --> 22:08.195
Not without the mayonnaise.
It's in the icebox.

22:08.400 --> 22:10.073
Oh, I'm feeling so good.

22:10.280 --> 22:11.680
I swear, I'm feeling so good.

22:11.880 --> 22:15.157
If I could carry a tune,
I'd sing a song.
Thank you very much.

22:15.360 --> 22:17.670
What a wonderful day
this has turned out to be.

22:17.920 --> 22:20.435
And I can't tell you
how happy I am about
you and me, Danny.

22:20.640 --> 22:23.553
If you think I'm happy,
you should see how happy
your mother is.

22:23.760 --> 22:26.720
Of course, she wouldn't
be happy if she saw the
sandwich I was... Thank you.

22:26.920 --> 22:28.560
You know, I think
it's all gonna work out.

22:29.000 --> 22:31.754
I mean, so much
has happened today,
so many wonderful things.

22:31.960 --> 22:34.873
You know, I think today is
the happiest day of my life.

22:35.080 --> 22:39.836
I know I already said that,
but it's just because I'm so happy.

22:40.080 --> 22:41.992
And this, this looks terrific.

22:42.200 --> 22:44.954
A terrific sandwich
for a terrific day.

22:45.160 --> 22:48.321
Ah, it's almost ready.
And now, Danny, we're gonna
have ourselves a treat, Danny.

22:48.400 --> 22:50.278
Hi, Burt. Hi, Danny.
Hi.

22:51.960 --> 22:52.960
Hi.

22:54.800 --> 22:57.918
So see you later, Danny.
You bet.

23:00.240 --> 23:01.560
I can't believe it.

23:01.760 --> 23:05.834
If I didn't see it with my own eyes,
the difference in your relationship.

23:06.040 --> 23:08.760
Oh, it's just night and day, Mary.
Just night and day.

23:08.960 --> 23:10.917
[♪♪♪]

